ce:section.ce:para:
The transmission electron micrograph (TEM) of the optimized batch of N-CDvaline formed by heating ethylene glycol and l-valine revealed nanoparticles of sizes in the range between 2 and 6 nm (Fig. 1
                     a and b). The selected area fast fourier transform (FFT) image at 10 nm scale is shown in the inset of Fig. 1b. Higher resolution transmission electron micrograph (HRTEM) of these carbon dots revealed ordered structure, attributable to arrangements of carbonaceous chains with spacing of 0.23 nm (Fig. 1c). Such types of structures are likely to be formed via self-assembly of transverse carbon chain inter-connected via hydrogen bonding [13,37,38]. It is suggested that the carbon chains in N-CDvaline is formed by acid catalyzed oligomerization of ethylene glycol and intermittently functionalized by bonding with the zwitterionic form of l-valine (Scheme-1a
                     ). A tentative mechanism of oligomerization of ethylene glycol triggered by the acidic protons of l-valine is given in Scheme-1b
                     . The 13C (Fig. 2
                     ) and 1H NMR (Fig. 3
                     ) were recorded to support the structures of the transverse carbon chains proposed in scheme-1a and 1b. The 13C NMR spectrum (Fig. 2a–e) confirms the proposed chemical structure. The peak at 63.17 ppm (Fig. 2a) in 13C spectrum corresponds to the –CH2OH or –CH2O types of carbon atoms in N-CDvaline; whereas the peak at 98.48 ppm (Fig. 2b) indicates the presence of ether (—C—O—C—) group. The peak at 115.55 ppm (Fig. 2c) indicates the presence of terminal alkenes (═CH2). The peaks at 143.36 ppm and 150.47 ppm (Fig. 2d) are attributed to the alkene carbon attached with the electronegative oxygen atom (—O—CH═). The peaks at 161.17, 166.16 and 169.69 ppm (Fig. 2e) are corroborated with the presence of carbonyl group in an ester moiety. In 1H NMR spectrum (Fig. 3a) two doublets observed at 0.78 ppm and at 0.825 ppm, together with a septate at 2.04 ppm (Fig. 3b) strongly suggested the presence of iso-propyl group in the as-synthesized nitrogen doped carbon dots. The isopropyl groups are part of the L-valine component, as shown in the Scheme 1a. The peak at 3.95 ppm (Fig. 3c) corresponds to the methylene proton attached with the O atom (i.e., –CH2—O—). The peak at 4.76 ppm (Fig. 3d) corresponds to the terminal vinylic -CH2 protons, as suggested in Scheme 1a. The strong peaks at 2.45 ppm and at 3.33 ppm are due to the solvent DMSO-D6 and the moisture content in the solvent, respectively. Further, for better understanding of the proposed structure of N-CDvaline, MS-QToF measurement was performed.
